@node "Overview" "Overview"
@title "GuideMaker Overview"
@tab 23
@{jcenter}@{bg Shine}Overview

@{jleft}@{pard}@{lindent 3}

@{_GM_} is an @{amigaguide} file creation utility.@{par}

It combines the Reaction Text Editor gadget and other Reaction GUI elements, the AmigaGuideAsync program interface, and control software that understands and can manipulate AG format files. The package is the beginnings of a visual development environment for AmigaGuide.@{par}

@{b}The information@{ub} is presented in three windows on the @{"Screen" LINK "GMScreen.jpg/MAIN"}:@{lindent 8}@{par}
1. The "Node List Window" has the nodes and global commands and gadgets for manipulating them.@{par}
2. The "Node Edit Window" contains the contents of the currently selected node and its local commands.@{par}
3. The "AmigaGuide Window" shows the formatted display.
@{lindent 3}@{par}

@{b}Why?@{ub}@{line}
I needed help in writing an AmigaGuide document. AG in spite of its flaws, is still the best way to add slick and quick context-sensitive help to your Amiga program.


However, the main reason I put @{_GM_} together now was to see if the new native PPC Modula-2 compiler I have been working on could be reasonably used for a non-trivial project. The answer seems to be:


     "Yes, but ..."@{lindent 36}@{par}
(It generates correct code quickly, but I've got my work cut out for me in slimming down the amount of code generated.)

@{lindent 3}@{par}
Nevertheless, @{_GM_} seems useful to me, and perhaps it could be to other OS4 developers/users interested in producing an AmigaGuide document.
@{par}

@endnode
@node "AmigaGuide" "AmigaGuide"

@{jcenter}@{bg Shine}AmigaGuide

@{jleft}@{pard}@{lindent 3}

@{amigaguide} may still have a place in the OS4+ Amiga environment. Even now, it seems to me that it offers a lot more than a text file displayed with NotePad, and is quicker than starting up a web browser to look at HTML or starting up AmigaPDF for a PDF document. It is good for interactive help within a program, and not too bad for longer documentation.


It does have many @{b}idiosyncrasies@{ub} and quirky problems. Sometimes It is difficult to predict exactly what the AG formatter will do, so is almost imperative that you continually check it's appearance as you write it. @{_GM_} will help in this.


The OS4 Autodocs on the AG DataType and AG Library give bare bones information, but the best source for a thorough course in how AmigaGuide works in practice is to be found in @{b}Frank Bunton's@{ub} "How_To_Write_Amigaguide" document. Look for it under "Docs/Help" at Aminet, named "aguidehowtowrite.lha".


@{_GM_} will successfully load most pre-existing AmigaGuide files. I've tried it on a number of OS4 associated files: Workbench.guide, Installer.guide in SYS:Locale, VinceED.guide, KingCON.guide, CygnusEd.guide, Lha28.guide, SGrab.guide.
(It actually caught an error in ImageFx.guide.)

@{par}
@endnode
@node "Installation" "Installation"
@{jcenter}@{bg Shine}Installation

@{jleft}@{pard}@{lindent 3}

Unpack the archive into the directory of your choice.


You will get the GuideMaker executable, GuideMaker.guide, and a few JPG files to which GuideMaker.guide has links.

@{par}
@endnode
@node "Requirements" "Requirements"
@title "GuideMaker Requirements"
@{jcenter}@{bg Shine}Requirements

@{jleft}@{pard}@{lindent 3}

1. Amiga OS4 (July 2007 update)@{line}
2. AmigaGuide (v40), distributed with AOS4@{line}
3. "T:" assigned to a  temporaries directory.

@{par}
@endnode
@node "Startup" "Startup"
@{jcenter}@{bg Shine}Startup

@{jleft}@{pard}@{lindent 3}

@{_GM_} is currently designed to start up from the @{b}CLI@{ub}, as no ToolTypes are yet supported.

@{lindent 9}@{par}
@{b}Template@{ub}:  "FILE,PUBSCREEN/K"

@{lindent 3}@{par}
If no @{b}FILE@{ub} is given, it will open up a file requester and ask for one. If the name given does not exist, it will create a new AG file.


If no @{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub} is given it will open on the default public screen.
@{par}
@endnode
@node "NodesWindow" "NodesWindow"
@{jcenter}@{bg Shine}Nodes Window

@{jleft}@{pard}@{lindent 3}


This is the @{"Nodes Window" LINK "GMNodeWindow.jpg/MAIN"}.


The @{b}top@{ub} part of the Nodes Window is for inserting the "global" AG commands that will apply to every node in the file (unless overridden by a node-local command within a node). The top three gadgets allow adding a new global command, modifying an existing one, and deleting a selected one.


The rest of the Nodes Window consists of a sequential list of the @{b}current nodes@{ub} in the file. Similar gadgets are here for adding new nodes, modifying a node's title, and deleting the selected node. The two additional gadgets are for moving nodes up or down in the list.


@{b}Double-click@{ub} on a node name and it will appear in the @{"Node Editing Window" LINK "EditingWindow"}.

@{par}
@endnode
@node "EditingWindow" "Node Editing Window"
@{jcenter}@{bg Shine}Node Editing Window

@{jleft}@{pard}@{lindent 3}

This is @{"Node Editing Window" LINK "GMEditWindow.jpg/MAIN"}.


The @{b}top@{ub} part of the Node Editing Window is similar to that of the Nodes Window, except that it is for node-local commands that apply to this node only.


The rest of the Node Editing Window is a Reaction Text Editor gadget containing the node contents. You can type in @{b}text@{ub} for display and embedded "@{b}attribute@{ub}" AG commands in the Editor, and you can use the drop-down gadget at the right to select from the list of attribute commands. After you enter the command's parameters, it will be inserted into the text at the cursor position.


(@{b}Note@{ub}: There is no vertical scroller in the Reaction Text Editor. If your text is longer than the window height, you can scroll the contents simply by moving the cursor position up or down at the limits of the editing area).


The @{b}"L" button@{ub} works similarly for LinkOp embedded commands, LINK, RX, RSX, and SYSTEM.


The @{b}"x" button@{ub} is an Undo-All for this node's text, removing all edits you have made since this node's contents were brought into the Node Editing Window.


The @{b}Next button@{ub} at the bottom will load the appropriate following node into the Node Editing Window - either the one specified by the \@{next xxx} node-local command, if any, or simply the sequentially next node if there is no such node-local command (and similarly for the @{b}Prev button@{ub}).


Note that the displayed name of the next or prev node appears in @{fg Fill}color@{fg Text} if a node by that name does not exist in the Guide file.


The @{b}right-pointing button@{ub} asks AmigaGuide to display this node in its @{"formatted window" LINK "FormattedDisplay"}.

@{par}
@endnode
@node "FormattedDisplay" "FormattedDisplay"
@{jcenter}@{bg Shine}Formatted Display

@{jleft}@{pard}@{lindent 3}

@{_GM_} produces the Formatted Display by writing out a file (GuideMakerTmp.guide) to the "T:" directory, consisting of only one node, the one currently residing in the Node Editing Window, and using the @{b}OpenAmigaGuideAsync()@{ub} amigaguide.library routine to display it.


@{b}Note@{ub}: The link buttons in this window are not active, except for links to files external to this AG file.

@{par}
@endnode
@node "Known Bugs" "Known Bugs and Deficiencies"
@{jcenter}@{bg Shine}Known Bugs and Deficiencies

@{jleft}@{pard}@{lindent 3}

@{u}            @{uu}@{line}
@{b}Bugs@{ub}
@{par}@{lindent 6}

Exceptions caused by program errors will be trapped and the @{b}Grim Reaper@{ub} displayed. If this happens, please click on the GR StackTrace button to determine where the error occurred, and then hit Continue Program.  @{_GM_} will attempt to abort "gracefully", giving you a chance to save the file before exit.


Unfortunately, some problems have been observed that do not allow this graceful exit:
@{lindent 9}@{par}
- The AmigaGuide display may hang the machine if fed badly formed node contents.

- I have seen an apparent Intuition screen deadlock the Reaction Text Editor 52.1 (in conjunction with @{_GM_}?), but can't reproduce it. There is no recovery for this.

- Don't open your guide file in @{i}Multiview @{ui} while you are editing it in @{_GM_}. Write out will fail when you exit @{_GM_} and edits will be lost.
@{par}@{lindent 6}

I think it is pretty stable otherwise, but it is always good practice to do a "@{b}Save@{ub}" from the program menu often enough not to lose too much of your work.

@{lindent 3}@{par}
@{u}                       @{uu}@{line}
@{b}Deficiencies@{ub}
@{par}@{lindent 6}

- The optional @{b}line number@{ub} parameter of a LINK is not in the input requester.@{line}
- Some AG commands are not yet included: \@{settabs <n>}, \@{beep}@{line}
- There needs to be better @{b}synchronization@{ub} between the three windows.@{line}
- There is no localization. Lo siento. Tal vez puedo ańadir alguno de Espańol si haya interés.@{line}
- <add your own to the list here>@{line}


@{lindent 3}@{par}
@endnode
@node "Future" "Future"
@{jcenter}@{bg Shine}Future

@{jleft}@{pard}@{lindent 3}

Assuming AmigaGuide continues to have a place in AOS4, improvements that have occurred to me:

@{lindent 8}@{par}
A little Localization@{line}

Auto-indexing@{line}
Export to HTML and/or RTF format.@{line}
Predefined macros@{line}
More interaction with the Text Editor Gadget@{line}
Warnings when ill-formed AmigaGuide is created@{line}
@endnode
